# TypeScript Standards

## Configuration / Settings Reading

- Use `idfConf.readParameter(param, scope?)` from `idfConfiguration` instead of `vscode.workspace.getConfiguration().get()` when reading extension or ESP-IDF-related settings.


## Comments / JSDoc

- Prefer self-documenting code (names + small helpers) over comments.
- Write comments for **intent / why / constraints / edge cases**; avoid narrating what the code already says.
- Avoid redundant docs (e.g. type and function docs restating the same concept).
- Keep JSDoc proportional. If it grows beyond ~8–10 lines, trim it or move narrative to `docs_espressif/` when appropriate.
- Avoid `@example` blocks in source by default; prefer “Find References” unless the API is non-obvious and used broadly.

```typescript
// ❌ Avoid: comment restates the identifier
// Convert bytes to kilobytes.
const kb = bytes / 1024;

// ✅ Prefer: name carries the meaning
const kilobytes = bytes / 1024;

// ❌ Avoid: property doc repeats name/type
type Flags = {
  /** True if enabled. */
  enabled: boolean;
};

// ✅ Prefer: omit or explain non-obvious semantics
type SettingOrigin = {
  /** Explicitly set by the user (distinguishes from defaults). */
  isExplicitlySet: boolean;
};
```

## Error Logging

- Use `Logger.error(message, error, "scope identifier")` for caught errors.
- Include a consistent scope identifier as the third argument (e.g. `"extension activate checkFoo"`).

